Firstly, not trying to be rude at all here, but this is mostly a site for questions that are more focused than this. The community here has a [Code of Conduct][1] which is something you&#39;ll want to read before continuing to post on the site (at very least, read [&quot;How do I ask a good question?&quot;][2]). Also, as pointed out in the comments, [MDN is a great resource for web development][3].

With that part out of the way, buckle in. I&#39;m about to point you in a direction, anyway. I just hope it is enough detail...


**Textboxes:**

Generally, for creating User Interface on the web, you will write [**HTML**][4]. Using your case, for example, we know you need three textboxes. I would use [`&lt;input&gt;` elements][5] like this:

**Step 1**

    &lt;input name=&quot;dob&quot; type=&quot;date&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;input name=&quot;amount&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.01&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;input name=&quot;interest&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.001&quot; /&gt;

**Step 2**

We can further wrap these to add text labels using [`&lt;label&gt;` elements][6], like so:

    &lt;label&gt;
      Date of Birth
      &lt;input name=&quot;dob&quot; type=&quot;date&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;
      Amount
      &lt;input name=&quot;amount&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.01&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;
      Interest
      &lt;input name=&quot;interest&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.001&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;/label&gt;

**Step 3**

Then, to link them together, we wrap them using a [`&lt;form&gt;` element][7]:

    &lt;form&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;
        Date of Birth
        &lt;input name=&quot;dob&quot; type=&quot;date&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;
        Amount
        &lt;input name=&quot;amount&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.01&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;
        Interest
        &lt;input name=&quot;interest&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.001&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;

**Step 4**

Finally, we need elements for calculation. I would use the aptly-named [`&lt;output&gt;` element][8] and a [`&lt;button&gt;` element][9] to submit the form:

    &lt;form&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;
        Date of Birth
        &lt;input name=&quot;dob&quot; type=&quot;date&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;
        Amount
        &lt;input name=&quot;amount&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.01&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;
        Interest
        &lt;input name=&quot;interest&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.001&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;
        Total
        &lt;output name=&quot;total&quot;&gt;0&lt;/output&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
    
      &lt;button type=&quot;submit&quot;&gt;Calculate&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;


**Calculation:**

As you see above, [`&lt;input&gt;`][5] is an interactive element that generally has a `name` and `value`. `value` can be updated by someone using your page or via [JavaScript][10], after the elements in question have been [fully loaded][11]. To update these elements and get values for your calculations via JavaScript, you would use something called the [DOM (Document Object Model)][12] and react to user input by &quot;listening&quot; to [events][13] (like &quot;click&quot;, for example). The form fires an event called &quot;submit&quot; when you click the &quot;Calculate&quot; button in the example above. We can use that instead of &quot;click&quot;, which makes it easier to handle everything inside the form (like the textboxes). For example:

    // Step 1: Create a JavaScript function (actually gets run later)
    const calcForm = form =&gt; {

      // Get values (and totalElement) from form.elements
	  const {
        amount: {value: amount},
        interest: {value: interest},
        total: totalElement,
      } = form.elements

      // Update the totalElement with interest * amount
      totalElement.value = (interest * amount).toFixed(2)
    }

    // Step 2: Wait for the DOM to fully load (so formElement exists)
    window.addEventListener(&#39;DOMContentLoaded&#39;, (event) =&gt; {

      // Step 3: Get form element using the &quot;js-form&quot; class
      const formElement = document.querySelector(&#39;.js-form&#39;)

      // Step 4: Run calcForm on &quot;submit&quot; event
      formElement.addEventListener(&#39;submit&#39;, (e) =&gt; {
        e.preventDefault()
        calcForm(e.target)
      })

      // Step 5: Run calcForm at start
      calcForm(formElement)
    })


One helpful thing to do is use classes as JavaScript &quot;hooks&quot;, so I also changed the form HTML to read: `&lt;form class=&quot;js-form&quot;&gt;` at this step. I use js- prefixes on classes to make it clear where it is used (that is, not [CSS][14]). You&#39;ll notice the line that says [`document.querySelector(&#39;.js-form&#39;)`][15]...this is what gets the `&lt;form&gt;` as an object in JavaScript.

Finally, putting all of this together, here&#39;s a working snippet with some basic (fully optional) [CSS][14] styling, but:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const calcForm = form =&gt; {
      const {
        amount: {value: amount},
        interest: {value: interest},
        total: totalElement,
      } = form.elements
      totalElement.value = (amount * interest).toFixed(2)
    }

    window.addEventListener(&#39;DOMContentLoaded&#39;, (event) =&gt; {
      const formEl = document.querySelector(&#39;.js-form&#39;)
      formEl.addEventListener(&#39;submit&#39;, (e) =&gt; {
        e.preventDefault()
        calcForm(e.target)
      })
      calcForm(formEl)
    })

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .form {
      display: grid;
      margin: 0 auto;
      width: min-content;
      justify-items: end;
      text-align: right;
      gap: 1rem;
    }

    .form__label {
      display: grid;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      font-weight: bold;
    }

    .form__input {
      width: 150px;
      text-align: inherit;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;form class=&quot;js-form form&quot;&gt;
      &lt;label class=&quot;form__label&quot;&gt;
        Date of Birth
        &lt;input class=&quot;form__input&quot; name=&quot;dob&quot; type=&quot;date&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;label class=&quot;form__label&quot;&gt;
        Amount
        &lt;input class=&quot;form__input&quot; name=&quot;amount&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.01&quot; value=&quot;50.00&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;label class=&quot;form__label&quot;&gt;
        Interest
        &lt;input class=&quot;form__input&quot; name=&quot;interest&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; step=&quot;0.001&quot; value=&quot;0.025&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;
      &lt;label class=&quot;form__label&quot;&gt;
        Total
        &lt;output name=&quot;total&quot;&gt;0&lt;/output&gt;
      &lt;/label&gt;

      &lt;button type=&quot;submit&quot;&gt;Calculate&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


